There would be few people in this country, of whatever political persuasion, who would argue against the contention that the taxi industry is a law unto itself. Every day, in thousands of places, taxi drivers break the law with impunity. Every day, many of them treat their passengers with the disdain of someone carting rubbish, rather than paying customers. And almost every day, someone dies in another taxi business-related assassination. They are SA’s homegrown mafia. But the actions this week by taxi organisations – in threatening a boycott of services unless the disaster coronavirus rules on social distancing are not...